==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sheaf
<hw>Sheaf</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A
sheave.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheaf</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sheaf
<hw>Sheaf</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Sheaves</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>sheef</ets>, <ets>shef</ets>,
<ets>schef</ets>, AS. <ets>sce⟦aacute⟧f</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>schoof</ets>, OHG. <ets>scoub</ets>, G. <ets>schaub</ets>, Icel.
<ets>skauf</ets> a fox's brush, and E. <ets>shove</ets>. See
<er>Shove</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A quantity of the stalks and
ears of wheat, rye, or other grain, bound together; a bundle of grain or
straw.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The reaper fills his greedy hands,⟦br⟧
And binds the golden <qex>sheaves</qex> in brittle bands.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any collection of things bound together; a bundle;
specifically, a bundle of arrows sufficient to fill a quiver, or the
allowance of each archer, -- usually twenty-four.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>sheaf</qex> of arrows shook and rattled in the case.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheaf</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sheaf
<hw>Sheaf</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To gather and bind into a sheaf;
to make into sheaves; <as>as, to <ex>sheaf</ex> wheat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheaf</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sheaf
<hw>Sheaf</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To collect and bind
cut grain, or the like; to make sheaves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that reap must <qex>sheaf</qex> and bind.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheafy</ent>⟦br⟧
